burial goods recorded during the Genroku excavation included a crown, {{ill|sword|ja|大刀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/sword|qq=}}, and mirrors. However, these were also reburied alongside the coffin{{Sfn|Okinaga Tomb (Heibonsha)|1991}}.

The tomb is estimated to have been constructed in the mid-to-late {{ill|5th century|ja|5世紀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/5th century|qq=}}, during the mid-Kofun period. It follows the Nagahama Chausuyama Kofun chronologically and predates the Kakigome Kofun{{Sfn|Tetsuro Tsujikawa|2006}}{{Sfn|Chiaki Mizutani|2013|pp=76–97}}. While it has been Historic Site1 as the tomb of {{ill|Hirohime|ja|広姫|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirohime|qq=}}, this attribution is considered unlikely due to discrepancies in the timeline{{Sfn|Okinaga Tomb (Heibonsha)|1991}}. 

== Excavation History ==
* Genroku 9 (1696): Discovery of a stone coffin and associated burial goods during temple renovations. Relics reburied at the Hori Residence{{Sfn|Okinaga Tomb (Kokushi)}}{{Sfn|Tetsuro Tsujikawa|2006}}.
* 1872 (Meiji 5): Inspection by the Ministry of Education, with sketches made of stone coffin fragments{{Sfn|Tetsuro Tsujikawa|2006}}.
* 1874 (Meiji 7): Official Historic Site as Okinaga Tomb by the Ministry of Education{{Sfn|Okinaga Tomb (Kokushi)}}.
* 1875 (Meiji 8): Mound construction at reburial site, officially recognized as a tomb{{Sfn|Okinaga Tomb (Kokushi)}}.
* 1883 (Meiji 16): Former burial site brought under Imperial Household Agency jurisdiction{{Sfn|Tetsuro Tsujikawa|2006}}.

