[[File:Okinaga-no-Misasagi, haisho.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Hirohime Okinaga Tomb Shrine}}{{small|Relics reburied in Genroku era; mound constructed and Historic Site1 as a tomb in Meiji era.}}]]
'''Muraida Kofun''' (村居田古墳) is an ancient [[:en:Kofun|Kofun]] located in [[:en:Maibara, Shiga|Maibara]], Shiga Prefecture. Its type is hypothesized to be [[:en:Zenpokoenfun|Zenpokoenfun]], and it is part of the Nagahama Kofun Cluster.

The actual individual buried in the tomb remains unclear. However, part of the site has been Historic Site1 by the [[:en:Imperial Household Agency|Imperial Household Agency]] as the tomb of [[:en:Hirohime|Hirohime]], empress of Emperor Bidatsu, the 30th [[:en:Emperor of Japan|Emperor of Japan]].

== Overview ==
[[File:Kouunji (Maibara), hondou.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Araryōzan Kōun-ji Temple}}{{small|Mound remains are adjacent to the temple's main hall.}}]]
Muraida Kofun is situated in the northeastern part of Shiga Prefecture, near the northern end of the Yokoyama Hills in the Hokoku region{{Sfn|Tetsuro Tsujikawa|2006}}. It is part of the Nagahama Kofun Cluster (Yokoyama Northern Kofun Cluster), which includes tombs such as the Nagahama Chausuyama Kofun and the Kakigome Kofun in Nagahama City{{Sfn|Tetsuro Tsujikawa|2006}}{{Sfn|Chiaki Mizutani|2013|pp=76–97}}. According to the *Sakata District Gazetteer* (*Sakata-gunshi*), the mound was discovered in Genroku 9 (1696) during renovations to the main hall of Araryōzan Kōun-ji Temple. A stone coffin was unearthed from the mound but later reburied at the current tomb site (Historic Site1 as Okinaga Tomb). During this discovery, much of the original mound was destroyed{{Sfn|Okinaga Tomb (Heibonsha)|1991}}, and the remaining parts of the mound are now managed by the Imperial Household Agency. No full-map_size investigations have been conducted due to this Historic Site{{Sfn|Okinaga Tomb (Heibonsha)|1991}}.

The mound's exact type is unclear due to erosion, but it is hypothesized to be [[:en:Zenpokoenfun|Zenpokoenfun]]{{Sfn|Tetsuro Tsujikawa|2006}}{{Sfn|Chiaki Mizutani|2013|pp=76–97}}. Surrounding the site, fragments of [[:en:Haniwa|haniwa]] (cylindrical haniwa) have been found{{Sfn|Hirohime Okinaga Tomb Group (Zoku Kofun)|2002}}{{Sfn|Tetsuro Tsujikawa|2006}}. Inside the mound, a {{ill|house-shaped stone coffin|ja|家形石棺|1=House-shaped Sarcophagus|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/house-shaped stone coffin|13=User:Immanuelle/House-shaped Sarcophagus|qq=}} made of Aso welded tuff (known as Aso Pink Stone) was discovered. This coffin, with its four protrusions for rope attachments, represents the easternmost example of such coffins{{Sfn|Tetsuro Tsujikawa|2006}}. 

burial goods recorded during the Genroku excavation included a crown, [[:en:大刀|sword]], and mirrors. However, these were also reburied alongside the coffin{{Sfn|Okinaga Tomb (Heibonsha)|1991}}.

The tomb is estimated to have been constructed in the mid-to-late [[:en:5th century|5th century]], during the mid-Kofun period. It follows the Nagahama Chausuyama Kofun chronologically and predates the Kakigome Kofun{{Sfn|Tetsuro Tsujikawa|2006}}{{Sfn|Chiaki Mizutani|2013|pp=76–97}}. While it has been Historic Site1 as the tomb of [[:en:Hirohime|Hirohime]], this attribution is considered unlikely due to discrepancies in the timeline{{Sfn|Okinaga Tomb (Heibonsha)|1991}}. 

== Excavation History ==
* Genroku 9 (1696): Discovery of a stone coffin and associated burial goods during temple renovations. Relics reburied at the Hori Residence{{Sfn|Okinaga Tomb (Kokushi)}}{{Sfn|Tetsuro Tsujikawa|2006}}.
* 1872 (Meiji 5): Inspection by the Ministry of Education, with sketches made of stone coffin fragments{{Sfn|Tetsuro Tsujikawa|2006}}.
* 1874 (Meiji 7): Official Historic Site as Okinaga Tomb by the Ministry of Education{{Sfn|Okinaga Tomb (Kokushi)}}.
* 1875 (Meiji 8): Mound construction at reburial site, officially recognized as a tomb{{Sfn|Okinaga Tomb (Kokushi)}}.
* 1883 (Meiji 16): Former burial site brought under Imperial Household Agency jurisdiction{{Sfn|Tetsuro Tsujikawa|2006}}.

